body:
r? @brson

(rust_highfive has picked a reviewer for you, use r? to override)

Wow, supercool! Thanks. 

By the way, would be possible to announce #rust-ru channel somewhere?
@mkpankov yeah, having it here would be good. It's on mozilla's IRC?
@steveklabnik Yes. This channel on Mozilla's IRC.
@steveklabnik  Ok, just to confirm: the channel is at Mozilla's server [here](http://client00.chat.mibbit.com/?server=irc.mozilla.org&channel=%23rust-ru)

I realized there are actually several language-specific channels, so we should add them in a new section, but I'll do that in a different PR

r? @brson
I think there should be an added disclaimer that these are not maintained by Rust developers, and that they may be out of date.
@sinistersnare Does "Community" not communicate that effectively enough?
Hi guys @kgv, @rust-kr, @KaiserY, @mkpankov I want to start translating to Spanish do you have any advice on the process to setup the env for translating?
@steveklabnik, no, I do not think that it is enough.
@goyox86 https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/tree/master/src/doc/trpl is all you need, just make them Spanish:)
r=me but seems like some comments may not be completely addressed yet

My thoughts is that by putting a huge disclaimer, we risk minimizing the hard work everyone is doing to translate the book. I think just saying "community" is enough to communicate the situation without being overly negative.
I am also going to add the non-english channels to the IRC list, but I need to figure out how to query for all rust related channels on moznet, and that's fine as a separate PR
@bors: r=brson rollup

Oh, I feel stupid for not bringing these issues up earlier.

Still, is this file reflected on the web somewhere? I feel it might be hard to actually discover these links.

Also, isn't it better to insert them directly to TRPL introduction for example, as AFAIK all of these translations are translations of just TRPL, not the entirety of the documentation.
@mkpankov it will be on http://doc.rust-lang.org/ tomorrow
